    "exptext": "<b>1873 — to liberate the depressed classes and make them conscious of their rights</b><br><br><b>Jyotiba Phule</b> was born in <b>1828</b> in a <b>Mali (backward caste) family</b> and organized a powerful <b>non-Brahmin movement</b>. He was critical of the prevailing Hindu religion and customs and made no distinction between non-Brahmins and untouchables.<br><br>He opened a <b>school for the untouchables in 1854</b> and started a private orphanage to help widows. He founded the <b>Satya Shodhak Samaj in 1873</b> to liberate the depressed classes and spread education among women and lower castes.<br><br>He wrote two critical works: <b>Sarvajanik Satyadharma Pustak</b> and <b>Ghulamgiri (1872)</b>. His other writings include <b>Dharma Tritiya Ratna, Ishara</b> and <b>Life of Shivaji</b>. He was also critical of the Indian National Congress for neglecting the weaker sections. <b>Periyar</b> composed a Ramayana in Tamil called <b>'Sachchi Ramayana'</b>.",
