    "quesimage": "",
    "exptext": "<b>Calcutta Session, 1917</b><br><br><b>Annie Besant</b>, born in <b>Ireland in 1847</b>, arrived in India in <b>1893</b> and became closely associated with the <b>Theosophical Society</b>. She established the <b>Central Hindu College at Banaras in 1898</b>. <b>Banaras Hindu University</b> was established in <b>1916</b> with the efforts of <b>Madan Mohan Malviya</b>.<br><br>She started the <b>Home Rule Movement</b> along with <b>Tilak in 1916</b> and published <b>Commonweal</b> and <b>New India</b>. She was chosen as the <b>first woman president of Indian National Congress</b> at the <b>Calcutta session of 1917</b>.<br><br>She felt the <b>Montagu-Chelmsford reforms</b> were a means to free India, but <b>Gandhi</b> thought them inadequate. As a result, at the <b>Congress Amritsar session</b>, she could not get through an amendment to the main political resolution. She also felt that <b>non-cooperation and boycott of foreign goods</b> would lead to terrible consequences. She did not attend the <b>Nagpur session of 1920</b> and in the last <b>13 years</b> of her life gave up active politics. She <b>died in 1933</b>.",
