    "quesimage": "",
    "exptext": "<b>K. Sridharalu Naidu — Madras, 1864</b><br><br>The impact of the Brahmo Samaj's message in South India led to the founding of the <b>Veda Samaj</b> (known as the <b>Brahmo Samaj of South India</b>) in <b>Madras in 1864</b> by <b>K. Sridharalu Naidu</b>, a Brahmin. He was inspired by <b>Keshub Chandra Sen</b> during the latter's visit to Chennai in 1864.<br><br>Among its teachings:<br>• Marriage and funeral rituals were <b>devoid of religious significance</b><br>• All sectarian views were <b>meaningless</b><br>• <b>Caste distinctions</b> needed to be thrown overboard<br>• People should abstain from <b>polygamy, child marriage</b>, and dance programmes of dancing girls<br><br>The Samaj also campaigned for <b>widow remarriage</b>. The movement became <b>moribund in the 1880s</b> after the demise of <b>Naidu and Iyengar</b>.",
