    "quesimage": "",
    "exptext": "<b>Baba Dayal Das (1783–1885) — worship of God as Nirankar (formless God)</b><br><br>The <b>Nirankari Movement</b>, initially an offshoot of Sikhism, was founded in the <b>1840s</b> by <b>Baba Dayal Das (1783–1885)</b>. He emphasised the worship of God as <b>Nirankar (formless God)</b>.<br><br>The <b>Namdhari Movement</b> began as an extended offshoot of the erstwhile <b>Kuka movement of the 19th century</b>. It was led by <b>Baba Ram Singh</b> and his disciple <b>Balak Singh</b>. The Namdharis encouraged <b>widow remarriage</b> and discouraged <b>dowry and child marriage</b>. They also contributed to the <b>freedom struggle</b>.<br><br>The <b>Singh Sabha</b> was founded by <b>Thakur Singh Sandhawalia</b> and <b>Gyan Singh</b> on <b>1st October 1873 at Amritsar</b>. Its objectives were:<br>• Counter <b>Christian missionary activities</b> and Hindu organizations' influence<br>• Introduce <b>modern education</b> and establish a chain of <b>Khalsa schools</b> across Punjab<br><br>The <b>Gurudwara Reform Movement</b> began after <b>1920</b>, forced the Government to pass the <b>Sikh Gurudwara Act in 1922 (amended 1925)</b>, giving control of Gurudwaras to Sikhs with the <b>Shiromani Gurudwara Prabandhak Committee (SGPC)</b> as the apex body.",
