    "correct": "2",
    "quesimage": "",
    "exptext": "<b>Consecration of a Shiva idol at Aravipuram by Sri Narayana Guru — defying caste restrictions</b><br><br>The <b>Aravipuram Movement</b> was launched by <b>Sri Narayana Guru</b> on the day of <b>Shivaratri in 1888</b>. He defied the religious restrictions placed on the <b>Ezhava community</b> and consecrated an idol of Shiva at <b>Aravipuram</b>.<br><br><b>Sri Narayana Guru</b>, born into a low-caste Ezhava family, studied Sanskrit, Malayalam, Tamil and astrology. The <b>Aravipuram Pratishtha</b> was historic because a member of a lower caste entered the temple and consecrated the Shiva image.<br><br>The organization he set up later became known as <b>Sri Narayana Dharma Paripalana Yogam (SNDP)</b>. His famous quote: <b>'One Religion, One Caste, One God'</b>.<br><br>His disciple <b>Sahodaran Ayyapan's</b> quote: <b>'No Religion, No Caste, No God'</b>.<br><br>In <b>November 1936</b>, the <b>Maharaja of Travancore</b> issued a proclamation throwing open all government-controlled temples to all Hindus. <b>Rajagopalachari</b> took a similar step in <b>Madras in 1938</b>. Under the mediation of <b>Gandhiji</b>, in <b>March 1925</b>, an agreement was reached with the agitators about temple entry with the Queen of Travancore.",
