    "exptext": "<b>B.R. Ambedkar — aggressive protest and political action</b><br><br>The <b>Mahar</b> are a numerically significant caste of Maharashtra, traditionally considered <b>untouchables</b>. Initially in the 19th century, the Mahar were led by <b>Baba Mavlankar</b>, but from <b>1920 onwards</b>, leadership was given to <b>B.R. Ambedkar</b>.<br><br>The <b>Depressed Classes Mission (1906)</b> of <b>V.R. Shinde</b> helped them by starting separate schools and hostels. Ambedkar adopted a strategy of <b>aggressive protest</b> and <b>political action</b>, rejecting the Gandhian approach of relying on change of heart of caste Hindus.<br><br>He organized several satyagrahas:<br>• <b>Mahad Satyagraha (December 1927)</b> — for rights of untouchables to draw water from public wells<br>• <b>Parvati Temple Satyagraha (1928)</b><br>• <b>Kalaram Temple Satyagraha (1930–35, Nasik)</b> with over <b>15,000 volunteers including 500 women</b><br><br>He demanded <b>separate electorate for Harijans</b> and burned <b>Manusmriti</b> to show indignation against orthodox Hindus. He organized the <b>first All-India Conference of Untouchables in May 1920 in Nagpur</b>.",
