    "quesimage": "",
    "exptext": "<b>Non-Brahmin Hindus — representation in government jobs and legislature</b><br><br>On <b>November 20, 1916</b>, the <b>South Indian Liberal Federation (SILF)</b> was formed by leading non-Brahmin citizens of Madras: <b>Dr. T.M. Nair, Sir Pitti Theagaraja Chetty</b> and <b>C.N. Mudliyar</b>.<br><br>Their joint declaration, the <b>Non-Brahmin Manifesto</b>, demanded the representation of <b>non-Brahmins in government jobs</b> — this was the <b>first cohesive demand for reservation</b> raised in India.<br><br>SILF launched a newspaper called <b>Justice</b> and was popularly known as the <b>Justice Party</b>. In the <b>1920 elections</b> for the Madras Legislative Council under the <b>Government of India Act 1919</b>, the party won as Congress boycotted the elections.<br><br>The <b>Madras Presidency Association</b> was formed in <b>1917</b> and demanded <b>separate representation for lower castes</b> in the legislature.",
