    "quesimage": "",
    "exptext": "<b>Drafting Committee of the Indian Constitution</b><br><br><b>Dr. Bhim Rao Ambedkar (1891–1956)</b> was born in an untouchable Dalit community called <b>Mahar</b> in Maharashtra. He was the first man to make a <b>scientific study of untouchability</b>.<br><br>In <b>1924</b>, he established <b>Bahishkrita Hitakarini Sabha</b>. He organized the <b>Independent Labour Party (1936)</b> on secular lines. He published the Marathi fortnightly <b>Bahishkrit Bharat (1927)</b> and organized the <b>Samaj Samta Sangh (1927)</b>.<br><br><b>Prime Minister Nehru</b> invited Ambedkar to be the <b>Law Minister</b> in the First Cabinet of Independent India. He was made the <b>Chairman of the Drafting Committee of the Indian Constitution</b>.<br><br><b>Article 17</b> of the Constitution <b>abolished untouchability</b>. He wrote the famous book <b>Annihilation of Caste (1936)</b>. As an expression of his disillusionment with Hinduism, he <b>embraced Buddhism in 1956</b> with his followers. He is rightly called <b>'Abhinava Manu' (Modern Manu)</b> and was awarded the <b>Bharat Ratna posthumously in 1990</b>. In <b>1942</b>, he founded the <b>All India Schedule Caste Federation</b>.",
